In particular, the Replicator starts prints by calibrating itself, which ends with the head at the front right corner of the print bed, after which it comes in on the diagonal to wherever it starts printing. comments.text: I just set my endstops so that the print head stops short of the clips. If you really want to let your machine continue to home to the absolute extreme of the bed  you could use 3 corner clips, and then 1 or 2 edge clips on the front left of the bed.  Just a simple flat hold down in maybe 1 or 2 inches from the homing corner.

Have you ever tried to cut a pill before? It's not the easiest thing in the world to do, and usually one or both of the halves go flying far away and you never can find them. I've had to cut my dogs allergy pills pretty frequently and I got tired of looking all over for the two halves, so I decided it would be simple enough to design and build a pill cutter. Of course I could've just bought one online for about $10 but why do that when I can make one? A few design requirements:
Plastic isnt strong enough to cut the pill itself, so I decided my design would use a standard razor blade that is available from any hardware for cheap
I wanted the sides of the cutter to be enclosed to that the pill halves wouldnt go flying
I wanted it to fit a variety of standard pills
Print without support material
*Be as simple as possible while still being effective Check out the design and prototype process on 3D Idea Forum http://www.3dideaforum.com/forum/household/projects/381-pill-cutter-designed-and-3d-printed
You will probably have to rotate or flip one or both of the parts to get the correct orientation for printing. I printed these on a Replicator 2 with 25% infill, .2mm layer height

  • The Mavic is about 25.5mm higher with attached accessories, and should now be on a level surface almost horizontal. To allow the front feet to lie flat on a flat surface, the legs are angled by about 5 degrees.
  • The rear leg should not negatively affect any nearby sensors, but I could not (yet) verify during a flight.
  • If replicas are too tight, try to print at slightly lower temperatures. Otherwise, try using slightly higher temperatures. Alternatively, you can adjust the material flow in the machine settings.
  • The front legs can also be protected against slipping and loss with a small piece of rubber band.
  • The nozzle diameter should not exceed 0.4mm.

The purpose behind this is to disable the battery charging functionality for all Android devices connected to the remote control. Simply stated: A 200 Ohm resistor in the 5 volt power circuit of the USB connection prevents the DJi Mavic remote control from charging any connected Android devices. "Adornment"?

Black 12mm sections of the end-blocks were printed as separate pieces and glued to the gray end-blocks to add a bit of adornment to the final product.

Design

This is similar to power supply end-blocks others have designed but was not sure if any would work as needed for my power supply. Using Fusion 360, I designed this for a 5 Volt DC power supply which will be used to power 5 Volt DC LED strips having individually addressed LEDs.

Multi-Colored End-Blocks

While testing out the fit for the power supply end-blocks, I cut out a 12mm section from the open end of one of the end-blocks in Slic3r and printed just the 12mm section. Since having the 12mm section (in black) next to the final end-block (in gray) on the power supply "looked so good" to me, I printed another 12mm section and glued one to each end-block.

These 12mm sections are not needed but I though the "adornment" added to the final result.

You could also possibly use "ColorPrint" at http://www.prusaprinters.org/color-print to 3D print multi-colored end-blocks if you can be around at the layer(s) you need to make the filament change. ColorPrint embeds special commands into your existing g-code files.

description.text:
I wanted colour coded female header pins to help those learning electronics to get familiar with the colour codes and build and debug circuits. It is also useful for those more experienced with electronics. This thing is a replacement for the usual housing for female header pins. It is designed for 2.54mm (0.1 inch) spacing PCB or veroboard. The customiser will allow you to choose the number of pins you require. For the colour change, I printed this on its side (unless your printer has a very fine nozzle you'll probably have to print in this orientation) and changed the material so you can print this without a dual extrusion printer. For the metal parts I simply removed these from standard female headers and pushed them into place with a pliers.

I printed this in PLA and had no problems soldering it (no issues with melting) although I was a bit more careful than usual.

At least for my printer (ultimaker 2), this is quite a challenging print. The walls are quite thin and there is a lot of fine detail. I would suggest printing slowly and print multiple items at once so each layer has time to cool. The customiser has additional fine tuning options which you may need to adjust for your particular printer. Definitely have a look at the part in layer view before printing as depending on the settings some features may not print correctly.

Students often find it difficult to wire up sensors and other electronic components. This thing aims to improve the experience by
-colour coding the pins for simplicity
-helping to reinforce the conventions for wire colour
-assisting in the debugging of the circuit

The file would be printed prior to the activity. It would be used on a breakout board or shield (such as one for an arduino) in conjunction with other components. The educator would explain the colour conventions for wiring electronics before introducing a board with these connectors. The students could then wire the circuit which should now be more intuitive than with standard female connectors

This is just a small component of what would be required for this activity. In particular, standard female headers are required to get the metal parts from. Also required is veroboard or PCBs, sensors microcontrollers, wires etc.

title: Wells turbine customizable
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
This is my own design of a 3D printable model of the classical Wells turbine. Turbines of this kind may be operated in bidirectional airflows and are the heart of OWC (Oscillating Water Column) wave power plants.
Printing the STL files you'll get a properly designed turbine with an outer diameter of 113 mm and an 8 mm axes bore. To run it, you'd put it on an axis into a tube and power it with an ordinary vacuum cleaner or - better - a leaf vac or with compressed air from either side. Use the 3-blade design for highest airflows (leaf vac) and the 7-blade design for low and middle airflows (house vacs). To give the design a fairly good starting behavior (which is an issue with this turbine type) I used appropriate NACA airfoil data in the blade and cap design. Have also fun with two of my videos showing this kind of turbiine in action as well as more sophisticated newer designs with self adaptive behaviour I'm holding a patent on. I'll try to present models for the newer designs in my further work. Feel encouraged to also leave feedback and comments on these. Air turbines: http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=lRwBGI_o11c
Water turbines: http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Djsl1uou6F8 The SCAD file offers sufficient parameters to let you choose your own sizes, blade number, NACA number and between half and full design, depending on your printing technique. The half design things might print easier on FDM printers. Print an upper and a lower (mirrorred) half and glue them together after print.

description.text:
Box for holding 2 5S Lipo batteries on the bottom of a board. 3 slots included for XT90 female jacks to be inserted into the box. Two of the 3 will be used for discharging during the charging process when it uses the balance leads to push voltage in and draws power through the main connection to pull it back down to get the cells level, the 3rd is going to be used as a place for a "switch" in the form of a looped male XT90 with a spark resistor in it. The batteries will be wired in series but without the extra male XT90 inserted it will have an open loop. Includes hole for passing wires to the ESC and hole for accessing the balance leads for charging. Screws and nuts are standard skateboarding screw and nut size but likely need longer than regular screws for reaching through the plastic since there are a few cm of solid plastic to go through before reaching where the nut gets locked in.

Update Added the updated box with the batteries lying flat to get more ground clearance also added a curve to the top so it fits tighter to the board.

After printing probably good to give it an acetone bath or "paint" with acetone "juice" but only do this if you take proper precautions to avoid blowing yourself up or knocking yourself out from vapors. description.text:
Remix of UNO Snug allowing assembly without board mounting screws. Board is held in place by centering pins and locked down with hold downs in top.

Print. Drop board in. Snap on top. Done!

The intent of this remix was to provide an enclosure for the following stacked components:

Adafruit Feather 32u4 Basic Proto
FeatherWing Proto
Adafruit 15x7 CharliePlex LED Matrix FeatherWing
Adafruit Sensiron SHT31-D Temperature & Humidity Sensor

Where the Feather was programmed to display the current temperature, updated every 5 seconds.

The basic case and wing top of the Adafruit Feather Box Enclosure were the initial source for this enclosure.

This remix involved narrowing and slightly lengthening the enclosure and reducing the wing top cutout to only display the LEDs of a CharliePlex FeatherWing. A few other modifications were also made as some options available in the basic case were not needed.

Many thanks to Adafruit for providing the Fusion 360 Archive file (Feather Box V2.f3z), the groundwork for this project!

Note that the photographs provided of the CharliePlex FeatherWing, when on, do not accurately reflect the display due to lighting issues when photographing light sources.

Components and Assembly

The following components were used:

Adafruit Feather 32u4 Basic Proto with Female Headers
https://www.adafruit.com/product/2771
Adafruit FeatherWing Proto with Stacking Headers
https://www.adafruit.com/product/2884
Adafruit 15x7 CharliePlex LED Matrix FeatherWing
https://www.adafruit.com/product/3163
Adafruit Sensiron SHT31-D Temperature & Humidity Sensor
https://www.adafruit.com/product/2857

The FeatherWing Proto board was wired to expose the 3V, GND, SCL, and SDA pinouts for connection to the SHT31-D sensor.

The Feather board was mounted onto the bottom of the enclosure and the sensor mounted on the end of the enclosure. The FeatherWing Proto board was then stacked on the Feather board and connected to the sensor. The CharliePlex FeatherWing was then stacked atop the FeatherWing Proto board and the enclosure top added.

description.text:
This is a Beam Combiner Mount for the K40 chinese 40W CO2 laser.

No drilling is needed, just some glue or double sided tape.

Bill of Materials:

  • Mini 5V Red Dot Laser 650nm (6x10mm), ~2 EUR:
    http://www.ebay.de/itm/171925923594
  • Beam Combiner Optic 20x2mm, ~50 EUR:
    http://www.ebay.de/itm/151644437138
  • 4 springs, I took mine from this set:
    https://www.amazon.de/gp/product/B009T1OTBM
  • M3 hex screws, nuts, washer
  • M2 allen screws, nuts, washer
  • Some glue and/or double sided tape

How to make one:

  • Print the ring (that's a bit difficult, but it works with support)
  • Put two M3 hex screws in the ring
  • Glue/tape the ring in the K40 laser hole
  • Check where the CO2 beam leaves the hole (using some paper)
  • Print the rest of the files (you probably need support for the main component)
  • Put the combiner optic in the main thingy and use 2 M2 screws with big washers to keep it in place
  • Put 4 M2 nuts in the main thingy
  • Glue/tape the plate on the side with the M2 nuts
  • Put the red dot laser in the hole
  • Mount the red dot laser using 4 M2 screws and 4 springs
  • Mount the whole thing on the ring and tighten the 2 M3 nuts a bit
  • Check where the CO2 beam leaves the hole in beam combiner and adjust the position on the ring to make it leave in the center
  • Put a piece of thermal paper on mirror 2, fire your laser and use the 4 M2 screws to adjust the position of the red dot

title: B-Struder - Bowden extruder with 40Tgear + U604ZZ bearing for 1.75 filament

description.text:
I had an all aluminium extruder (from ebay), and it worked fine, it was just a bit off whenever I needed to insert a new filament, because of the gap between the gear and the bowden tube, so the filament went everywhere except were intended...

Looking around Thingiverse, I found some great designs I liked, so I chose and studied these next 3 good examples, mixed them to fit the parts from the Ebay aluminium extruder that I had, and then tweaked it some more to get what I desired:

  • B'Struder: Universal Bowden 1.75mm Extruder by tempo502 - for the way the filament goes inside the lever, and overall clean and very clever design concept.
  • 3Dator Bowden Extruder by 3Dator - very compact, also a great design, but I wanted to use only one screw+spring with the lever guiding system of the B'Struder, so from the 3Dator I picked the idea of the MR105ZZ support bearing, and the side locking lever with the pointing arrow.
  • Minimalistic Mk7 replacement by whosawhatsis - for the simplicity of the acting lever mecanism, less is more.

Modified or added:

The two lever design makes it really easy to use this setup, with very little force required, and totally safe from sharp gear teeth.

There's a spring tension adjustable screw, to be able to adjust the extruder pre-load.

The side lock lever should remain closed, to protect the toothed gear from intruding fingers (doh!), but can be rotated to open for gear inspection, alignment, and cleaning.
When fully open, it can lock the arm lever in an open position (see pictures), allowing to fully insert or remove the filament with both hands free, without having to manually secure the arm lever.

The filament entry on the top of the moving lever was designed with a cone shape, to ease filament entry point, you can just put the filament straight in, but you can also apply a PC4-M6 pneumatic fitting if you wish.

This top PC4-M6 (PTFE fitting) is optional, it's only needed if you have a bowden tube to guide the filament to the printer (or from a storage box).
This is my first version with PC4-M6, these have an inner ring that acts as a bump stop, where filament edge could possibly get stuck when inserting, but in normal it usually passes just fine, I have no problems with these.
I've ordered some PC4-M5 to see if they're any better, and will update the files if needed.

The MR105ZZ, the support for this bearing (fixed lever) , and the side locking lever are also optional, the extruder will work without them (as the original source B'Struder), but it works much better and safer with them.

If you have a Deltabot and want to make an Flying extruder, or position your extruder in the top center of the deltabot, then I also made this one:
http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2249240

Comments are welcome, and please post your make :)..

2017-05-06 Update: slightly modified the part for the MR105ZZ bearing support, with an added 1mm lip to better secure the bearing in place, because I had one of them pop out from the motor axle and disappear somewere... and still haven't found it. The small lip will prevent this from happening.

Printed sucessfully with PLA using a 0.8mm nozzle (Deltabot 300),
Also printed fine with ABS, using a 0.4 nozzle in a Mini Kossel (+ 10mm brim +heatbed).

For ABS it is advised to scale the parts up to 101 or 102% scaling, because ABS shrinks after printed, but this depends on your material choice.
See the first picture, and notice the small gap between the MR105ZZ bearing and the black ABS plastic? Doh! I forgot to scale it up... oh, well, whatever, nevermind, it works fine.

The smaller parts are best printed in pairs, to better allow part cooling. I printed them all x2, then assembled one of the extruders for me, and the other one for a friend.

The M5 washer is very small and thin, and it's to be inserted on the motor shaft, as a spacer between the toothed gear and the MR105ZZ bearing. I printed 4x at once (for part cooling).

The arm lever contains a small spacer inside the bearings opening, to be inserted between the 2x 623zz bearings used for arm rotation. This spacer stops the bearings center parts from being crushed by screw over tightening.

Clean up the 3mm holes for the motor mount, with 3mm drill bits (by hand), just to clean them out and make it easier for the M3 bolts to pass through to the motor, but there should be no need to drill the 3mm hole for the spring tensioning screw.

Don't clean the hole for the U604ZZ bearing, it's meant for the M4 12mm screw to tap into the plastic. If needed, you may use a 3.5mm drill bit to clean the inside of this hole.

Remove integrated support that is designed inside the lever hole for the U604ZZ bearing. It should break up easily, it's only there to support bridging. I also used a small flat file to smooth this area.

See the posted pictures for the assembly order.

Besides the plastic for the printed parts, these are the parts used, most are easily found in ebay:

1x bearing MR105ZZ (5 x 10 x 4mm)
1x extruder spring, 7.5mm width, 20mm long, with 1.3mm wire
2x M3 large flat washers, 9mm outer diameter
1x M3 nylon locking nut (for spring tensioner)
1x M3 8mm stainless steel round head phillips screw (to motor mount, under the lever)
1x M3 12mm stainless steel round head phillips screw (for spring tensioner)
3x M3 25mm stainless steel round head phillips screw
1x M4 12mm stainless steel round head phillips screw (for the U604ZZ bearing)
1 or 2x PC4-M6 PTFE fitting (M6 screw, for 4mm PTFE tube, 2mm inner hole)
1x Nema 17 Stepper Motor

description.text:
Updates 30/07/2017
All the pieces were reuploaded. No significant changes were made, only chamfers and similar stuff. No dimensions were changed. Old model and new one are completely compatible with each other.

Updates 28/07/2017
Uploaded a cutaway view to make assembly easier. The inner bars should be epoxi or CA glued to the inner piece of the assembly.

This is a a different X Axis Belt Tensioner for Anet A8. It's based on the one by WedgeSD.

CHANGES:

-The bars (guides) of the inner piece now are separated from the piece itself, so you can print the inner piece vertically and the bars horizontally. They should be glued with epoxi,or CA using the spacer if desired to keep them aligned. (Watch out so the spacer doesn't stick to the glue)

-The back part of both main pieces now is completely flat, so it leaves a smooth finish and there's no need of supports.

-The knob can be use with any X or Y tensioner.

NEEDED:
-M4x20 hex bolt
-M4 hex nut
.M4 washers (x2) (optional)
-20mm spring around the M4 bolt
-M3x25mm bolt for the idler pulley
-M3 washers (x6) (optional)

ASSEMBLY:
Check cutaway side view (third picture) for better understanding.
M4 washers can be put at each side of the spring.
M3 washers can be put between M3 bolt/nut and printed parts, between inner and outer case and at each side of the idler.

WORKS WITH:
Fully compatible with either toothless or toothed idler pulley. Thanks to @simonsays1 for the input.

Any feedback is welcome!

description.text:
Special thanks to kameya for sharing his build, I've gotten a lot of use out of it.

I did have a few issues I wanted to fix, the caps refused to stay on and I was afraid of pushing them too hard, pushing the nozzle into the container. Also, I didn't want my filament between the container and my printer to be exposed to the humidity, and wanted a better way to prevent kinks in the filament as it traveled between the container to my printer.

All you'll need are the materials kameya suggested, some PC4-M6 Male Straight Pneumatic Connectors (I got mine from Amazon, Witbot) and some 2mm/4mm tubing.

There are 3 pieces, the 1st has threads on the inside and outside. Obviously, the inside is for the pneumatic connector, the outside for the cap. As kameya said, you don't really need the third piece, but it doesn't hurt.

I liked his idea of having a little cavity in the cap so it grabs onto the filament, preventing it from falling back into the box. I just didn't realize that when you screw my caps back on, it twists the bit of filament out of the cavity. No worries though, my caps are big enough you can kink the end of it, which imo works a little better. Just cut it off next time you want to use it.

If you want a copy of the design, pm me. I drew it up in Rhino3d, so I can export it to most any file type you like.

Keep layer at .1mm (.15mm?) if you want to print the threads well. I would test out printing some nuts and bolts first to see if your printer can handle printing threads. If you can control the size of the perimeter shells (like Simplify3d's Horizontal Size Compensation), bring it in a little, you don't want to twist the nozzle so much it breaks the glue bond.

The third piece I printed at .28mm layer height.

Follow Kameya's instructions for Filament Storage Box DIY http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1372828, you can use his spool holders. I do advise you to score with a razor blade any areas you'll be hot-gluing, on the container and the parts.

Last month, we talk about how to charge lipo battery , from the article you have learned charge lipo battery is not easy thing, we should take more carefully. Today, we will give you some advises about how to discharge batteries.

the battery fire

  1. Don't discharge Batteries at amperage rates higher than specified on Batteries' labels.

  2. Don't allow the temperature of Batteries to exceed 140°F during discharge. Adequate cooling for Batteries is required, especially when discharging at or near maximum rates.

  3. Don't discharge Batteries to voltage below which they are rated by the manufacturer when measured under load (connected to the vehicle or a charger capable of discharge). Batteries discharged to a voltage lower than the lowest approved voltage may be damaged, resulting in loss of performance and potential fire when Batteries are charged.

  4. Don't discharge battery to a level below 3V per cell under load.

For Tattu series batteries which are used for Unmanned Aircraft System, The recommended cut off voltage is 3.5V per cell.

5.Don't leave battery unattended during the discharging process. During the discharging process, user should monitor the process constantly and react to potential problem that may occur.

  1. In case of emergency, discontinue the process immediately, disconnect the battery, place it in a safe area, and observe it for approximately one hour. This may cause the battery to leak and the reaction with air may cause the chemicals to ignite, resulting in a fire. A safe area should be outside of any building or vehicle and away from any combustible materials. A battery can still ignite even after one hour.

  2. User need to check the conditions of the battery before use it or discharge it. Stop using it if user found the cells are not balanced or cells are puffing or weeping.

And finally, don't over discharge the battery, over discharge the battery maybe let the battery damage or fire, so please take more carefully to discharge batteries

Requires a small zip tie.

I recommend applying some hot glue to the area that sits on your frame, letting it cool off a little bit, then pressing it on your frame to get the curvature.   • I measured the tubes on my 1985 road bike, so it's designed to wrap around standard round steel tubing: average(28.85 mm downtube, 29.01 mm seat tube, 25.56 mm top tube) = 27.81 mm generic tube
  • zip tie was 1 mm thick, 2.55 mm wide. Scaled both dimensions by 115% as well.

Functionally similar to this (https://www.amazon.com/Origin8-Plastic-Cable-Guides/dp/B000AP0AFK).

The brake version relies on a 4.95 mm diameter brake cable housing. Everything else is virtually the same.

I measured my hydraulic line (Shimano), & it was about 4.97 mm in diameter, so it should work with the brake version.

Leave a little cutout for the cable to snap in/out. I don't trust the 3D printed material to withstand this more than a couple times unless you get one of those elastic filaments, which I don't care to test. Maybe someone should remix it.

description.text:
This is a cover for the FIRST Robotics Competition Power Distribution Panel, which is a required part of the FRC control system and produced by Cross the Road Electronics.
A common problem on FRC robots is a lack of space to mount electronics, thanks to them often being given a low priority during the design phase.
The PDP takes up the most real estate of any of the required components, leaving less space on an electronics panel for speed controllers.

This thing is designed to make the impact of the PDP minimal, while satisfying all rules and possibly offering extra features.
Up to 6 Victor SP speed controllers can be mounting to the panels, as well as this voltage meter from Adafruit: https://www.adafruit.com/product/575 on the correct printed part.

As the panels flip up to allow access to the Snap-Action breakers, several robot inspectors have ruled this as satisfying R48 from section 8 of the 2017 FRC Game Manual: The PDP, associated wiring, and all circuit breakers must be easily visible for Inspection.

title: Smile - You're on Earth (Laser Etched Sign)

description.text:
I often walk by "Smile, You're on Camera" signs and they always make me smile - so this is my version of that. I intend to hang it up surreptitiously around decrepit buildings in SF, or just on my front gate - we'll see!

There are a few ways you can cut it:

  • Etched (and engraved to pop the etched letters more).
  • Just engraved, no etching (faster)
  • Engraved, and then use stain to color in the letters later.
  • 2 layers: An engraved layer, stained, plus a cut layer, glued on top. That's what the photo shows.

It depends on your desired look and speed. Cut it on wood to be most eco-friendly, please. :)

For my photobooth business I build a radio buzzer which will used to start the counter of my photobooth. I used an original buzzer from EATON and changed the lower housing. I added a batterie box and enough space for a PocketWizard PlusX electronic board.
If you are wondering about the blue tape which sticks at the bottom of the housing. My bed is little bit too narrow to the nozzle.

Of course, I could construct the whole buzzer but I had one in my cellar since ages, before I bought a 3D printer. The next one will be of course a complete construction.

Parts list:
Buzzer: https://www.amazon.de/FUß-GROBHANDTASTER-1S1Ö-FAK-R-KC11/dp/B0014DQI5S/ref=sr_1_1?ie=UTF8&qid=1491981036&sr=8-1&keywords=eaton+buzzer
Batterie holder: https://www.amazon.de/gp/product/B000PEJQOW/ref=oh_aui_detailpage_o02_s00?ie=UTF8&psc=1
Switch: https://www.amazon.de/gp/product/B00IKDQ0SK/ref=oh_aui_detailpage_o01_s00?ie=UTF8&psc=1
PocketWizard PlusX: https://www.amazon.de/PocketWizard-Plus-X-Transceiver-433MHZ/dp/B00CFL93SC/ref=lp_1700280031_1_11?srs=1700280031&ie=UTF8&qid=1491984228&sr=8-11

For the batterie holder you have to change the cable guiding. Push the cables back thru the holes and put each cable to their own side (left/right). If you will take a look into the printed housing you will see why. You can see also that I cutted the holder in halfes, that the batteries are change able without pulling the holder out of the housing.

The 8mm hole can be used with a 3/8 screw tab. After cutting the thread, it fits on the most tripods (only with a 3/8 UTC screw mount).
